postcontent: Bought these a while back at 45$ plus tax. Had planned on modifying but never got around to it. Pretty fun the way they are set up now. Its a full-auto fire simulated in a "nearly" harmless toy, with a single stack style mag and twenty rounds of flying foam-cushioned fury..... VERY FUN to play with around the house, especially if someone else has another nerf gun as well.  I have two in the box with everything included and one I've assembled, has batteries in it, and used a few times (I took off scope and lost one disc) but nothing else. I dont really want to get rid of but my girlfriend finds them extremely annoying and said they've gotta go. Also, if you check out YouTube, their are modifications that can change the guns performance. Simple enough for a middle school kid to explain and diagram the electronic wiring mods. Thanks for looking.

title: For Sale:  Metro Arms American Classic II
location: North of Quad Cities, Quad Cities, Illinois
postcontent:
I have for sale a Metro Arms American Classic II 1911 chambered in 45 ACP. I purchased this brand new in the middle of March for $415. I've put exactly 350 rounds through it. When I took it out the first two times I experienced a dozen failures to feed. It would eject the spent cartridge fine, but would not fully return to battery when feeding the next round. It was a tight fitting weapon, and was pretty cold out, and the first two times I took it out I did so without field stripping the weapon and cleaning it even though I just bought it....so I chalked it up to a fluke. I field stripped it, and gave it a good scrubbing, having found it loaded with oil. A little frog lube on the rails and a couple other lubrication points, manually cycling the weapon, and I haven't had a problem since. 



My very first time reassembling after having cleaned it, I put a slight "idiot scratch" in it while trying to re-insert the slide stop. When I say slight, I mean slight. I could probably buff it out in two minutes....but the bluing on the Metro Arms American Classic II isn't exactly known for being top notch as demonstrated by the bluing being worn off underneath the safety and slide stop. It is in very good condition. It's not at all a bad weapon...in fact I really enjoy it. I had plans lined up to send it to a gunsmith for a few customizations that I wanted to get done (trigger, night sights, mainspring housing)...but that idea has been cancelled in favor of knocking out an unplanned bill.



Here are the specs:


Caliber: .45 ACP
Overall Length: 8.375”
Barrel Length: 5”
Height: 5.5”
Width: 1.25”
Weight (empty): 37.28 oz.

Slide: 4140 Hammer Forged Steel
Single Action
Novak-Style Rear Sight

Extended Slide Stop
Beavertail Grip Safety
Combat Hammer
Combat Trigger
Front & Rear Serration
Extended Thumb Safety
Throated FORGED STEEL Barrel

It comes with the case, trigger lock, spent casing, user manual, as well as the factory 8 round magazine (Act Magazine) and two Chip McCormick stainless steel Shooting Star 8 round magazines that I purchased. I am willing to meet in Carroll County, Whiteside County, and Rock Island County. I could meet you in the IL QC's in a *good neighborhood* 5 days a week. I would be willing to meet in Carroll County or Whiteside County pretty much any day of the week. I would also be willing to travel to Ogle, or Stephenson County as well if we can work out a day and time. All State and Federal laws apply (72 hours minimum waiting period, valid FOID card and FOID check, bill of sale). We will meet in a location that ensures the safety of both of us (i.e. no alley deals, no crap neighborhoods, would prefer a gun shop or range if possible in order for you to inspect the weapon in a safe and lawful fashion without causing unnecessary alarm). Not interested in trades at this time.

The BUL M-5 is a M1911 clone pistol made by Israeli firearms manufacturer BUL Transmark. M-5s are made in "carry" models for personal defense and "competition" models for sporting use (particularly IPSC competitions).

Based on the M1911.45 ACP, this version is specifically designed to compensate for the 1911's heat absorption in high temperature environments with a polymer frame.

BUL also provided the polymer frame to other firearms manufacturers for production of Springfield Armory, Kimber Polymer and Charles Daly Polymer 1911 pistol lines.

Multi gun trades welcome, the worst I can do is say no. Whatcha got? This is a ground up project I built from an extra DPMS receiver, and the parts list is a doozy. The R.E.P.R. rifle allows a marksman to perform assaulter duty with the 16” barreled upper installed, and quickly switch to a sniper role simply by changing to the 20” barreled upper. The extra upper receiver assembly can be carried in a backpack and takes up less room and weighs less than carrying a separate rifle. 
The R.E.P.R. rifle utilizes our patented self-regulating, short-stroke gas-piston operating system, ensuring unparalleled reliability in the harshest theaters of operation. A side-mounted charging handle allows the shooter to perform reloads without removing their eyes from the target, and prevents any gas blowback to the face when using a suppressor. The ARM-R™ rails are easily removable and reinstalled with a hex key and provide a 100% return to zero for optics and lasers.
